headline: Is it time for Mueller to wrap up his investigation?
subHeadline: Rudy Giuliani says he will not let the president sit down with the special counsel without first seeing the FBI documents. Former U.S. attorney Joe diGenova speaks out on 'Watters' World.'

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Welcome to "Watters' World." I'm Jesse Watters. The mainstream media had the worst week it has had all year. So much to get to, we're just going to have to take it one thing at a time. First daughter Ivanka tweeted this photo of her and her 2-year-old son, sparking massive backlash with critics calling the photo insensitive in light of her father's immigration policy. I don't know what that means -- in a report about missing immigrant children, which turned out to be false.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Critics are saying that the post is really tone deaf in that the reports of families being separated at the Mexican border.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And that was fake news, but the most despicable attack coming from comedian Samantha Bee.

utterances.speaker: SAMANTHA BEE,COMEDIAN
utterances.sentences: Ivanka Trump who works at the White House chose to post the second most of oblivious tweet we have seen this week. You know, Ivanka, that's a beautiful photo of you and your child, but let me just say, one mother to another, do something about your dad's immigration practice, you feckless (inaudible). He listens to you. Put on something tight and low cut and tell your father, to (inaudible) stop it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They bleeped the C -- word if you hadn't heard that yet. The President calling at a double standard after the cancellation of "Roseanne" earlier this week, tweeting, "Why aren't they firing no talent Samantha Bee for the horrible language used on her low ratings show? A total double standard, but that's okay, we are winning, and we will be doing so for a long time to come." First lady Melania Trump also taking to Twitter clearing up fake news stories speculating about her whereabouts following her recent surgery, writing, "I see the media is working overtime speculating where I am and what I am doing. Rest assured, I am here at the White House with my family feeling great, and working hard on behalf of children and the American people." Joining me now to break this all down, the founder of Turning Point USA, Charlie Kirk and media reporter for The Hill, Joe Concha. Charlie, welcome to "Watters' World."

utterances.speaker: CHARLIE KIRK, TURNING POINT USA
utterances.sentences: It's a pleasure to be here in your world.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There it is, you've been practicing that move, I see.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: That's right. It's a little bit slower usually.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's okay, you know, you have a lot to learn.

utterances.speaker: JOE CONCHA, THE HILL
utterances.sentences: The circumference.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Joe has been on the show once or twice. So, let's get to the Samantha Bee thing. Her ratings have deteriorated. She's lost about half her audience in about a year. So, I just think this is a Hail Mary to see if she can get back on track and it looks like it backfired.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: I mean, is she supposed to be funny? I mean, the left has killed comedy and late night comedy. I mean, these are just endless angry rants from was-be comedians that are now putting politics over any sort of entertainment value whatsoever. I mean she is shamelessly going after Ivanka. The double standard, as the President pointed out is so abhorrent and so apparent and you are seeing some advertisers back away from it, but this is a common trend.  Look, I think this shows far more entertainment than any of these other crazy late-night television shows at this hour.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, thank you, Charlie, we are going to have you back on next week.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Thank you, Jesse. The shameless baiting worked very, very well.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Joe, what do you think? I mean, the President is calling her to be fired. Do you think she should be fired? Do you think TBS carved that little spot for her to get nasty. That's their prerogative.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: You say you said TBS carved that spot and you're right. Remember, that was scripted. That is in teleprompter. There are checks and balances where several people had to look at that and say, "You know, that's okay."

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That was not live.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Right, exactly. So, Laura Ingraham or Katie Pavlich or Michelle Malkin -- what happens if they make that comment about any Obama whether it be Michelle or her daughters or Hillary Clinton or Chelsea Clinton?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They're gone.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: So, you asked my question, yes. What should happen? Bee keeps her job, right? There's not even a suspension. That will be the compromise that I would see, go take a vacation for a while.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Because we did suspend a talking head on Fox News for using a derogatory slur against President Obama. I think he got a week or two off. So, there are standards here, to quote the great Tomi Lahren, "If it wasn't for the double standards, the left would have no standards at all."   I want to show you guys these little illegal alien kids in cages that the media went bonkers over earlier in the week. Here is a tweet from former Obama speechwriter, Jon Favreau. He says, "This is happening right now and the only debate that matters is how we force our government to get these kids back to their families as fast as humanly possible." It turns out, Charlie, this picture is from the Obama years.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: It was from his administration.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: What I love most about the picture, look up at the left-hand corner, 2014. None of these liberals said anything when these images were actually released back, when it was happening under the Obama years. And look, this again, this goes to this whole idea that the liberals have selective outrage about these issues. They have such a pathological hatred of this President that they will make up their own facts and their own circumstances to try to go after him, but going to the kind of this whole -- this whole common theme, when a conservative dares does something wrong, they get fired and their life is ruined. When a liberal steps out of line, they have to just issue a fake apology and they get to keep their (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's because the left protects its gunslingers. They will do anything to make sure they stay and keep hurling insults at the right, and they make excuses because they believe their political cause is righteous.  But these cages, Joe, this is the kind of mistake that I think really destroys what little credibility the fake news media has left.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Yes, and the problem is that even after the mistake is made, there is no contrition. We apologize, I got it wrong, without excuses. So, we always talk about how trust in the media is at an all-time low. I would say, we used the word hatred before, hatred of the media is at an-time high because this was -- I am not going to say it was intentional, but after the fact, there was no apology, and this is the whole problem with media right now, very little fact checking, tweeting before thinking, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And if you look at the polling, people trust the President more than the mainstream media. There is also -- speaking of not trusting the mainstream media, another character, Jim Acosta, he's the CNN White House correspondent who you see yelling things and trying to get his face on camera.  I got it, Jim you are a budding superstar over there. So, you remember Kim Kardashian paid a visit to the White House and talked about prison reform. Here was his reaction, roll it.

utterances.speaker: JIM ACOSTA, CNN
utterances.sentences: Forget about the fact that Kim Kardashian is here at the White House today and what planet that is anything resembling normal because it's not. She shouldn't be here talking about prison reform. It is very nice that she is here, but that's not a serious thing to have happened here at the White House.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So, a celebrity in 2018 talking about prison reform at the White House, that is illegitimate, but here is what he said about a celebrity talking about prison reform just a few years before.

utterances.speaker: JOHN LEGEND, MUSICIAN
utterances.sentences: I am going to push the President to get more involved in criminal justice reform.

utterances.speaker: ACOSTA
utterances.sentences: If you change your mind about running for office, give CNN the scoop.

utterances.speaker: LEGEND
utterances.sentences: I will, I will.

utterances.speaker: ACOSTA
utterances.sentences: John Legend...

utterances.speaker: LEGEND
utterances.sentences: Don't hold your breath.

utterances.speaker: ACOSTA
utterances.sentences: We might just a little bit.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Take a look at Jim.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Oh, my goodness. I mean, they are going -- Jim Acosta, he is my favorite fake journalist that just hangs around the press pool. I think the President just enjoys having him around for the double standard and for calling him out for all of this. But look, the President did the right thing to take the meeting with one of the most of powerful international celebrities. She has a legitimate cause, not just prison reform, but she has been fighting for the rightful pardon of Alice Marie Johnson, and I think -- look, CNN and Jim Acosta, they can't possibly wrap their head around the fact that a leftist type celebrity can actually interface with a Republican President, so they are trying everything they possibly can to delegitimize it.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: And remember, he is not an opinion host. He's the senior chief White House correspondent. He got a promotion earlier this year, right, and he had the audacity to go on Jimmy Kimmel just a couple of weeks ago and claimed that he was just as tough on President Obama than he was on President Trump.  Now, here is the real punch line, when you look at ratings from last May, May of 2017 to May of 2018, CNN has lost one-quarter of its viewers, 25% gone. And you can't say it's been a slow news cycle over the last year. It's been the best news cycle ever up here in this industry, 25% in total viewers, 35% on what's called the demo, that's 25 to 54 year olds that advertisers cover most, more than a third gone. Where did they go? They don't like being told that reporters are reporters when they are opinion hosts and advocates like Jim Acosta.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right, I mean, just on it, Jim, you are with her, we all get it. The "Roseanne" show unfortunately, for a lot of people that worked on the show was canceled because of some really despicable things Roseanne said about Valerie Jarrett. She compared Valerie Jarrett to an ape, not good. They canned her immediately. But look how the mainstream media tried to smear Donald Trump with Roseanne Barr.

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN
utterances.sentences: We know what Donald Trump thinks, we know what Roseanne Barr thinks. It's racist. They are exhibiting racist behavior.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: It was a great move yesterday. The thing that sort of is the background of all this is that the President can be racist and nothing happened to him

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Roseanne's show canceled because she tweeted out racist stuff. You know who I blame for this? Donald Trump. That's who.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Tens of millions of people voted for him after he showed his cards for years.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Are you suggesting that they are racist?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: All the people who voted for Donald Trump are racist?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right, so just so many unfortunate things said at that montage. That's like blaming Bernie Sanders when the Bernie bro shot up Steve Scalise. you cannot make that connection with any sort of responsible integrity as a media reporter.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Precisely, I mean, this is the left who tries everything they can to loop any sort of bad behavior of someone that is on the center right immediately with the President.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yet they won't give the President any credit for the good thing that happens.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Never.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They only smear him with the negatives.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Well, make no mistake. This President has done far more for black American in his short Presidency than Obama did in eight years. Black unemployment at an all-time low, you see wages going up, you see an urban revitalization plan. He's going to get prison reform passed, which Obama refused to do. He's pardoning people that have been unjustly put in prison for racial bias, going back, you know, with the pardon of this famous boxer.  So, look, I think there is a common theme here which is the left wants to continue this narrative of racism because that's all they can possibly have. All they count is this (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They don't have a slogan, they don't have a jobs plan, they don't have a healthcare plan -- well, actually, the healthcare plan is free healthcare for everybody. I really didn't like the woman at the end there that said that all Trump voters in America are racists.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Isn't that amazing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Amazing.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Sixty five million people that voted for President Trump in 2016 did so because they think that the guy that they are voting for is a racist. Instead of the fact, to your point, that Donald Trump had a message that resonated in Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Ohio and Michigan and Hillary Clinton said vote for me because that guy is bad. No, by the way, Roseanne made comments about Susan Rice back in 2013 that were very similar to the one she made about Roseanne in 2018 -- the problem is, President Trump wasn't even a candidate in 2015, was he ever even called out for anything, so how could she -- how could Donald Trump be possibly -- it is possible for Roseanne when she has been doing this well before Trump was a President.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I mean, Roseanne botched "The National Anthem." She did the little Hitler mustache. I mean, she has been whacked for a while, I can't blame Donald Trump for that and neither should anybody else. But CNN is blaming Donald Trump for ruining the White House sports and fitness day because they say he's not fit. Listen to this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: The President is having this event here at the White House today highlighting health and fitness while questions are being raised about the President's own health and fitness. We are told that the chef in the White House kitchen had been told to limit calorie and fat intake in terms of the meals that they prepare for the President. He has traded his well-done steaks that he usually drowns in ketchup with dover sole and those cheeseburger he eats after he plays a round golf now only come with a bottom bun and no longer the top half of the bun. When he does go play a round of golf, he uses a cart instead of walking the whole leg like some people choose to do. So, a great deal of irony here today.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: CNN fat shaming President Trump on sports (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: You know what I love it, questions are being raised -- no one is raising these questions.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: CNN is raising them.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: They do this all the time. We have inside sources. No you don't. You are just making stuff up, I mean, questions being raised. You're the only person that cares about this. You and your four editorial producers that are trying to destroy this President.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: And that's a health skit.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Parody has become news. Folks, we're reporting live from the White House, his caloric intake is being watched, and everyone would laugh.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: The next thing you expect from CNN is that they are going to say that the President gets two scoops of ice cream when everybody else get -- wait, they already get that.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Oh, that's right, they already...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh look at that swing. Look at that swing.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Or that he only drinks nine things of Diet Coke every -- oh, they already did that, too.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes, what was the last President -- remember when he got caught working out in the gym.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: That was working out?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: He was curling about 10-pound weights and I think we saw the first pitch he threw was the Chicago White Sox game. I didn't see a lot of criticism there, or when he bricked -- he went two for 20 at the White House playing basketball. I didn't hear a lot about his fitness then.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Or Bill Clinton for that matter, the last check, looked like he was in his second trimester and we never heard anything about that either.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's not nice, Joe.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: No, I am just saying that. This President currently, and Bill Clinton for that matter had a lot of energy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's right.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Had and has, so, who cares if they're a little overweight. He's 71 years old.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: The guy works hard.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: And yes, he is high energy.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: And let's not forget the stamina. The rallies he's doing, the meetings he is hosting. He has such an unbelievable schedule, and again, he is in his 70s, and yet, the media has these ridiculous questions are being raised. No one cares.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And didn't his doctor say he was the most of fit President of all time.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: Yes, without a doubt.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The best heart, the best brain, I mean, the doctor said that. That he's fine.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: Genetics. Genetics.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Great genetics. Best genetics.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.sentences: And the doctor under three -

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.sentences: The best genetics. And the doctor, who was the doctor under Presidents, he was attacked for his report as if he was lying for him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There it is. All right, boys, I'll check in with you guys later. Up next spy gate outrage. Stay tuned.

utterances.speaker: JOHN SOLOMON, EXECUTIVE VICE PRESIDENT, THE HILL
utterances.sentences: The efforts to begin targeting and reach out to Trump campaign officials to gain intelligence on Russia that would ultimately justify the investigation began weeks and maybe months before the FBI had a formal predicate. There were contacts going on by people identified as informers and informants, people who provided information began much, much earlier than July 31st. That's the first part. The second part is as the investigation was just starting to ramp up, there are internal FBI documents showing FBI agents talking about the White House trying to take over the investigation.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: New reports questioning when and how an FBI spy came to be involved with the Trump campaign and how this will impact the Mueller probe moving forward. The President slamming that investigation and its soaring costs, tweeting, "AP has just reported that the Russian hoax investigation has now cost our government over $17 million. And going up fast. No collusion except by the Democrats." Joining me now, former US Attorney Joe diGenova, and Philippe Reines. Joe, I now question this entire investigation because what they said was the beginning of the investigation, this Papadopoulos comment to this Australian diplomat about -- he said he had dirt -- doesn't add up because now, we know the FBI was running spies at the campaign months beforehand. What does that mean to you?

utterances.speaker: JOE DIGENOVA, FORMER US ATTORNEY
utterances.sentences: Well, I don't think there is any doubt that to a reasonable United States Attorney, what you have here is an out of control CIA and FBI doing counter-intelligence investigations against American citizens in the united states and abroad without a proper predicate and without authority in an effort to start another investigation so that they can do damage to the Presidential candidate of the other party.  I don't think there is any doubt based on the available public evidence that John Brennan, James Clapper, James Comey and others worked together to try to start a counter-intelligence investigation against the Trump campaign, and that in the end, in order to get that done, they fabricated information, fed it to people overseas who were American citizens who then mouthed information about that which was picked up by the FBI and used in FISA warrants. So, when all is said and done, what we have here is let's have a nice Federal grand jury run by a competent person, either a senior Justice Department official, a US attorney or a special counsel and let's get Brennan, Clapper, Comey, and all these folks in front of a grand jury so they can explain themselves. And I am not calling for anybody to be indicted. I just want truthful testimony under oath in front of a grand jury, and if indictments result, fine. If they don't, then we'll get an explanation about what happened here.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: We want as much transparency on that side as there has been on the Trump side because the President's campaign, Philippe has been very forthcoming with the special counsel's office. Millions of documents turned over, a lot of people testifying, and it's been pretty long since this thing has been going on, and now we know from some of these FBI texts between Page and Strzok that, "The White House is running this." Meaning the White House is running the investigation. We can even put the text up on the screen. "The White House is running this." What does that mean to you, Philippe? I mean, that goes all the way to the top now.

utterances.speaker: PHILIPPE REINES, AMERICAN POLITICAL CONSULTANT
utterances.sentences: Well, I want to first respectfully disagree with Joe on something he said about no reasonable US Attorney would do this because both Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein and Bob Mueller were US Attorneys, in fact Rod Rosenstein's previous job was US Attorney, I believe Maryland. But in terms of your question, I think there is a problem here. We all forget where this started. This starts with Russia trying to screw around with us. What happened from there is American intelligence, counter- intelligence and law enforcement trying to stop them.  The so-called spy gate is flipped on its head. The spying was done by Russia on America, what the FBI tried doing is preventing it. I am not exactly sure why the President and the White House have internalized this as some kind of hunt.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Okay, let's just say that's true that they were trying to prevent all of these Russians from messing with the election. Did they do a good job? Number one. Number two, have any Russians been indicted for collusion? They were indicted for calling Hillary Clinton names on Facebook and dressing up with a little Hillary for prison costume and running around Florida at a rally. These are not high-level Russian spies colluding with the Trump campaign, Joe. After two years, wouldn't there actually be evidence of Russians colluding if that was the object? If it was to get Russians for doing bad things?

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.sentences: Yes, and of course it would have leaked by now if there were evidence of it. But the point is, the FBI and the CIA to the extent that it was working overseas were not trying to stop the Russians from doing anything. Many of the Obama administration officials have bemoaned the fact that President Obama didn't do enough to stop the Russians from meddling in the campaign. But when you look the FBI and see what they did and what they now say they were trying to do as James Clapper said, "We were only trying to help the Trump campaign." That's not what you do. You don't start a counter-intelligence investigation against an American Presidential candidate. What you do is, you go to that candidate's campaign and the candidate, and the FBI and you say, Mr. Candidate, we think the Russians are trying to influence your campaign. We are giving you a defensive briefing. We would like to you take defensive measures. Prophylactic measures against the Russians. But the Bureau didn't do that. That's not what they were doing. They were investigating the Trump campaign.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Let me ask Philippe. Philippe, why didn't the FBI go to the Trump campaign in May or April or whatever and say, "Listen, we are getting some word that the Russians might be trying to pull some dirty tricks with your guys or with your team, hey, heads up."

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.sentences: I would flip it on its head and say two things. First, why wouldn't the Trump campaign say, "Hey, FBI, we have got some weird context coming our way." I served in government for more than a dozen years and (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: What were the weird contexts coming their way?

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.sentences: People e-mailing you say, "I have dirt on Hillary Clinton." I mean, that's pretty clear.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Wait, who e-mailed who? And said, "I have dirt on Hillary Clinton."

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.sentences: Somebody e-mailed Don, Jr., a Russian e-mailed Don Jr., "We have dirt On Hillary Clinton and he said, "I love it." Especially if it is for the summer. Look, Joe is (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But you know how suspicious that is? If you are Don, Jr., you are a businessman, you are just looking for anything you can get on Hillary, and the woman that comes in gets a special visa approved by Loretta Lynch before the meeting, meets with Fusion GPS, the dossier author and then after the meeting meets with Fusion GPS's President? Doesn't that seem like a little bit of a setup to you, Joe?

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.sentences: Well, I don't think there is any doubt that the activities here are very questionable. They are inexplicable. They do not comport with traditional law enforcement and trade craft of spy. What they comport with is an effort to subvert the campaign of the opposing candidate. And let me just say, it would be one thing if this were just sort of a simple story, but it's not because when you go back to July 5, 2016, and James Comey's famous news conference where he accuses Hillary Clinton of a series of crimes, and then exonerates her, whatever the Russians were trying to do, they couldn't have done anything worse than what James Comey did on that day. He gave a blow to the solar plexus to the Clinton campaign far beyond anything that either Donald Trump or the Russians could have done.

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.sentences: Joe, you can't see me nodding, but I am nodding vigorously.

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.sentences: Well, there is nothing not to nod about. The bottom line is this, while all that is going on, James Comey, John Brennan and James Clapper are trying to figure out how to subvert the candidacy of the opposing candidate. And I must say, there is absolutely irrefutable evidence now that that's exactly what they were doing. And I am perfectly happy by the way, to have a grand jury look at it and make all the decisions necessary about whether or any of that was illegal. And I'll tell you, I just think right now, watching the fight between McCabe and Comey about who lied about what during all of this tells you exactly what kind of leadership we had at the FBI and the Department of Justice in the Obama administration -- a disgraceful bunch of dirty cops.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes, Philippe is not a big fan of James Comey either and I think he will admit that. He had come to "Watters' World" as are most Democrats and I always will say that Hillary would have fired Comey probably quicker than Donald J. Trump.

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.sentences: Why didn't Obama fire Comey after the July 5th press conference? He shouldh have been fired...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: A lot of questions. REINES; You and I would be sitting here talking about obstruction of something else. I mean, the problem with 2016 is you have a lot of people...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Listen, Philippe, we have got to run ,but the only thing Trump obstructed was Hillary getting into the White House. Up next, a judge ordered him out of his parents' home. And we are going to check with this 30-year-old, Michael Rotondo on his house hunt.

utterances.speaker: EMANUEL
utterances.sentences: Live from "America's News Headquarters," I am Mike Emanuel. Fox News obtaining a letter sent in January from President Trump's legal team to special counsel Robert Mueller arguing the President cannot be forced to testify into the investigation into Russian meddling in the 2016 election. They also argue that Mr. Trump could not have committed obstruction because he has absolute authority over all Federal investigations. A US delegation in Beijing this weekend to talk trade as fears of a global trade war escalate. utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: It was from his administration.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: What I love most about the picture, look up at the left-hand corner, 2014. None of these liberals said anything when these images were actually released back, when it was happening under the Obama years. And look, this again, this goes to this whole idea that the liberals have selective outrage about these issues. They have such a pathological hatred of this President that they will make up their own facts and their own circumstances to try to go after him, but going to the kind of this whole -- this whole common theme, when a conservative dares does something wrong, they get fired and their life is ruined. When a liberal steps out of line, they have to just issue a fake apology and they get to keep their (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's because the left protects its gunslingers. They will do anything to make sure they stay and keep hurling insults at the right, and they make excuses because they believe their political cause is righteous. But these cages, Joe, this is the kind of mistake that I think really destroys what little credibility the fake news media has left.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Yes, and the problem is that even after the mistake is made, there is no contrition. We apologize, I got it wrong, without excuses. So, we always talk about how trust in the media is at an all-time low. I would say, we used the word hatred before, hatred of the media is at an-time high because this was -- I am not going to say it was intentional, but after the fact, there was no apology, and this is the whole problem with media right now, very little fact checking, tweeting before thinking, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And if you look at the polling, people trust the President more than the mainstream media. There is also -- speaking of not trusting the mainstream media, another character, Jim Acosta, he's the CNN White House correspondent who you see yelling things and trying to get his face on camera. I got it, Jim you are a budding superstar over there. So, you remember Kim Kardashian paid a visit to the White House and talked about prison reform. Here was his reaction, roll it.

utterances.speaker: JIM ACOSTA, CNN
utterances.utterance: Forget about the fact that Kim Kardashian is here at the White House today and what planet that is anything resembling normal because it's not. She shouldn't be here talking about prison reform. It is very nice that she is here, but that's not a serious thing to have happened here at the White House.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So, a celebrity in 2018 talking about prison reform at the White House, that is illegitimate, but here is what he said about a celebrity talking about prison reform just a few years before.

utterances.speaker: JOHN LEGEND, MUSICIAN
utterances.utterance: I am going to push the President to get more involved in criminal justice reform.

utterances.speaker: ACOSTA
utterances.utterance: If you change your mind about running for office, give CNN the scoop.

utterances.speaker: LEGEND
utterances.utterance: I will, I will.

utterances.speaker: ACOSTA
utterances.utterance: John Legend...

utterances.speaker: LEGEND
utterances.utterance: Don't hold your breath.

utterances.speaker: ACOSTA
utterances.utterance: We might just a little bit.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Take a look at Jim.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Oh, my goodness. I mean, they are going -- Jim Acosta, he is my favorite fake journalist that just hangs around the press pool. I think the President just enjoys having him around for the double standard and for calling him out for all of this. But look, the President did the right thing to take the meeting with one of the most of powerful international celebrities. She has a legitimate cause, not just prison reform, but she has been fighting for the rightful pardon of Alice Marie Johnson, and I think -- look, CNN and Jim Acosta, they can't possibly wrap their head around the fact that a leftist type celebrity can actually interface with a Republican President, so they are trying everything they possibly can to delegitimize it.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: And remember, he is not an opinion host. He's the senior chief White House correspondent. He got a promotion earlier this year, right, and he had the audacity to go on Jimmy Kimmel just a couple of weeks ago and claimed that he was just as tough on President Obama than he was on President Trump. Now, here is the real punch line, when you look at ratings from last May, May of 2017 to May of 2018, CNN has lost one-quarter of its viewers, 25% gone. And you can't say it's been a slow news cycle over the last year. It's been the best news cycle ever up here in this industry, 25% in total viewers, 35% on what's called the demo, that's 25 to 54 year olds that advertisers cover most, more than a third gone. Where did they go? They don't like being told that reporters are reporters when they are opinion hosts and advocates like Jim Acosta.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right, I mean, just on it, Jim, you are with her, we all get it. The "Roseanne" show unfortunately, for a lot of people that worked on the show was canceled because of some really despicable things Roseanne said about Valerie Jarrett. She compared Valerie Jarrett to an ape, not good. They canned her immediately. But look how the mainstream media tried to smear Donald Trump with Roseanne Barr.

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN
utterances.utterance: We know what Donald Trump thinks, we know what Roseanne Barr thinks. It's racist. They are exhibiting racist behavior.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: It was a great move yesterday. The thing that sort of is the background of all this is that the President can be racist and nothing happened to him

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Roseanne's show canceled because she tweeted out racist stuff. You know who I blame for this? Donald Trump. That's who.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Tens of millions of people voted for him after he showed his cards for years.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Are you suggesting that they are racist?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Yes. Yes.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: All the people who voted for Donald Trump are racist?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, so just so many unfortunate things said at that montage. That's like blaming Bernie Sanders when the Bernie bro shot up Steve Scalise. you cannot make that connection with any sort of responsible integrity as a media reporter.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Precisely, I mean, this is the left who tries everything they can to loop any sort of bad behavior of someone that is on the center right immediately with the President.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yet they won't give the President any credit for the good thing that happens.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Never.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They only smear him with the negatives.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Well, make no mistake. This President has done far more for black American in his short Presidency than Obama did in eight years. Black unemployment at an all-time low, you see wages going up, you see an urban revitalization plan. He's going to get prison reform passed, which Obama refused to do. He's pardoning people that have been unjustly put in prison for racial bias, going back, you know, with the pardon of this famous boxer. So, look, I think there is a common theme here which is the left wants to continue this narrative of racism because that's all they can possibly have. All they count is this (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They don't have a slogan, they don't have a jobs plan, they don't have a healthcare plan -- well, actually, the healthcare plan is free healthcare for everybody. I really didn't like the woman at the end there that said that all Trump voters in America are racists.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Isn't that amazing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Amazing.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Sixty five million people that voted for President Trump in 2016 did so because they think that the guy that they are voting for is a racist. Instead of the fact, to your point, that Donald Trump had a message that resonated in Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Ohio and Michigan and Hillary Clinton said vote for me because that guy is bad. No, by the way, Roseanne made comments about Susan Rice back in 2013 that were very similar to the one she made about Roseanne in 2018 -- the problem is, President Trump wasn't even a candidate in 2015, was he ever even called out for anything, so how could she -- how could Donald Trump be possibly -- it is possible for Roseanne when she has been doing this well before Trump was a President.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, Roseanne botched "The National Anthem." She did the little Hitler mustache. I mean, she has been whacked for a while, I can't blame Donald Trump for that and neither should anybody else. But CNN is blaming Donald Trump for ruining the White House sports and fitness day because they say he's not fit. Listen to this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: The President is having this event here at the White House today highlighting health and fitness while questions are being raised about the President's own health and fitness. We are told that the chef in the White House kitchen had been told to limit calorie and fat intake in terms of the meals that they prepare for the President. He has traded his well-done steaks that he usually drowns in ketchup with dover sole and those cheeseburger he eats after he plays a round golf now only come with a bottom bun and no longer the top half of the bun. When he does go play a round of golf, he uses a cart instead of walking the whole leg like some people choose to do. So, a great deal of irony here today.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: CNN fat shaming President Trump on sports (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: You know what I love it, questions are being raised -- no one is raising these questions.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: CNN is raising them.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: They do this all the time. We have inside sources. No you don't. You are just making stuff up, I mean, questions being raised. You're the only person that cares about this. You and your four editorial producers that are trying to destroy this President.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: And that's a health skit.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Parody has become news. Folks, we're reporting live from the White House, his caloric intake is being watched, and everyone would laugh.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: The next thing you expect from CNN is that they are going to say that the President gets two scoops of ice cream when everybody else get -- wait, they already get that.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Oh, that's right, they already...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh look at that swing. Look at that swing.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Or that he only drinks nine things of Diet Coke every -- oh, they already did that, too.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, what was the last President -- remember when he got caught working out in the gym.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: That was working out?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He was curling about 10-pound weights and I think we saw the first pitch he threw was the Chicago White Sox game. I didn't see a lot of criticism there, or when he bricked -- he went two for 20 at the White House playing basketball. I didn't hear a lot about his fitness then.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Or Bill Clinton for that matter, the last check, looked like he was in his second trimester and we never heard anything about that either.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's not nice, Joe.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: No, I am just saying that. This President currently, and Bill Clinton for that matter had a lot of energy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's right.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Had and has, so, who cares if they're a little overweight. He's 71 years old.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: The guy works hard.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: And yes, he is high energy.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: And let's not forget the stamina. The rallies he's doing, the meetings he is hosting. He has such an unbelievable schedule, and again, he is in his 70s, and yet, the media has these ridiculous questions are being raised. No one cares.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And didn't his doctor say he was the most of fit President of all time.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: Yes, without a doubt.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The best heart, the best brain, I mean, the doctor said that. That he's fine.

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: Genetics. Genetics.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Great genetics. Best genetics.

utterances.speaker: KIRK
utterances.utterance: And the doctor under three -

utterances.speaker: CONCHA
utterances.utterance: The best genetics. And the doctor, who was the doctor under Presidents, he was attacked for his report as if he was lying for him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: There it is. All right, boys, I'll check in with you guys later. Up next spy gate outrage. Stay tuned.

utterances.speaker: JOHN SOLOMON, EXECUTIVE VICE PRESIDENT, THE HILL
utterances.utterance: The efforts to begin targeting and reach out to Trump campaign officials to gain intelligence on Russia that would ultimately justify the investigation began weeks and maybe months before the FBI had a formal predicate. There were contacts going on by people identified as informers and informants, people who provided information began much, much earlier than July 31st. That's the first part. The second part is as the investigation was just starting to ramp up, there are internal FBI documents showing FBI agents talking about the White House trying to take over the investigation.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: New reports questioning when and how an FBI spy came to be involved with the Trump campaign and how this will impact the Mueller probe moving forward. The President slamming that investigation and its soaring costs, tweeting, "AP has just reported that the Russian hoax investigation has now cost our government over $17 million. And going up fast. No collusion except by the Democrats." Joining me now, former US Attorney Joe diGenova, and Philippe Reines. Joe, I now question this entire investigation because what they said was the beginning of the investigation, this Papadopoulos comment to this Australian diplomat about -- he said he had dirt -- doesn't add up because now, we know the FBI was running spies at the campaign months beforehand. What does that mean to you?

utterances.speaker: JOE DIGENOVA, FORMER US ATTORNEY
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't think there is any doubt that to a reasonable United States Attorney, what you have here is an out of control CIA and FBI doing counter-intelligence investigations against American citizens in the united states and abroad without a proper predicate and without authority in an effort to start another investigation so that they can do damage to the Presidential candidate of the other party. I don't think there is any doubt based on the available public evidence that John Brennan, James Clapper, James Comey and others worked together to try to start a counter-intelligence investigation against the Trump campaign, and that in the end, in order to get that done, they fabricated information, fed it to people overseas who were American citizens who then mouthed information about that which was picked up by the FBI and used in FISA warrants. So, when all is said and done, what we have here is let's have a nice Federal grand jury run by a competent person, either a senior Justice Department official, a US attorney or a special counsel and let's get Brennan, Clapper, Comey, and all these folks in front of a grand jury so they can explain themselves. And I am not calling for anybody to be indicted. I just want truthful testimony under oath in front of a grand jury, and if indictments result, fine. If they don't, then we'll get an explanation about what happened here.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We want as much transparency on that side as there has been on the Trump side because the President's campaign, Philippe has been very forthcoming with the special counsel's office. Millions of documents turned over, a lot of people testifying, and it's been pretty long since this thing has been going on, and now we know from some of these FBI texts between Page and Strzok that, "The White House is running this." Meaning the White House is running the investigation. We can even put the text up on the screen. "The White House is running this." What does that mean to you, Philippe? I mean, that goes all the way to the top now.

utterances.speaker: PHILIPPE REINES, AMERICAN POLITICAL CONSULTANT
utterances.utterance: Well, I want to first respectfully disagree with Joe on something he said about no reasonable US Attorney would do this because both Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein and Bob Mueller were US Attorneys, in fact Rod Rosenstein's previous job was US Attorney, I believe Maryland. But in terms of your question, I think there is a problem here. We all forget where this started. This starts with Russia trying to screw around with us. What happened from there is American intelligence, counter- intelligence and law enforcement trying to stop them. The so-called spy gate is flipped on its head. The spying was done by Russia on America, what the FBI tried doing is preventing it. I am not exactly sure why the President and the White House have internalized this as some kind of hunt.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, let's just say that's true that they were trying to prevent all of these Russians from messing with the election. Did they do a good job? Number one. Number two, have any Russians been indicted for collusion? They were indicted for calling Hillary Clinton names on Facebook and dressing up with a little Hillary for prison costume and running around Florida at a rally. These are not high-level Russian spies colluding with the Trump campaign, Joe. After two years, wouldn't there actually be evidence of Russians colluding if that was the object? If it was to get Russians for doing bad things?

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.utterance: Yes, and of course it would have leaked by now if there were evidence of it. But the point is, the FBI and the CIA to the extent that it was working overseas were not trying to stop the Russians from doing anything. Many of the Obama administration officials have bemoaned the fact that President Obama didn't do enough to stop the Russians from meddling in the campaign. But when you look the FBI and see what they did and what they now say they were trying to do as James Clapper said, "We were only trying to help the Trump campaign." That's not what you do. You don't start a counter-intelligence investigation against an American Presidential candidate. What you do is, you go to that candidate's campaign and the candidate, and the FBI and you say, Mr. Candidate, we think the Russians are trying to influence your campaign. We are giving you a defensive briefing. We would like to you take defensive measures. Prophylactic measures against the Russians. But the Bureau didn't do that. That's not what they were doing. They were investigating the Trump campaign.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Let me ask Philippe. Philippe, why didn't the FBI go to the Trump campaign in May or April or whatever and say, "Listen, we are getting some word that the Russians might be trying to pull some dirty tricks with your guys or with your team, hey, heads up."

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.utterance: I would flip it on its head and say two things. First, why wouldn't the Trump campaign say, "Hey, FBI, we have got some weird context coming our way." I served in government for more than a dozen years and (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What were the weird contexts coming their way?

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.utterance: People e-mailing you say, "I have dirt on Hillary Clinton." I mean, that's pretty clear.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wait, who e-mailed who? And said, "I have dirt on Hillary Clinton."

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.utterance: Somebody e-mailed Don, Jr., a Russian e-mailed Don Jr., "We have dirt On Hillary Clinton and he said, "I love it." Especially if it is for the summer. Look, Joe is (inaudible)...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But you know how suspicious that is? If you are Don, Jr., you are a businessman, you are just looking for anything you can get on Hillary, and the woman that comes in gets a special visa approved by Loretta Lynch before the meeting, meets with Fusion GPS, the dossier author and then after the meeting meets with Fusion GPS's President? Doesn't that seem like a little bit of a setup to you, Joe?

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't think there is any doubt that the activities here are very questionable. They are inexplicable. They do not comport with traditional law enforcement and trade craft of spy. What they comport with is an effort to subvert the campaign of the opposing candidate. And let me just say, it would be one thing if this were just sort of a simple story, but it's not because when you go back to July 5, 2016, and James Comey's famous news conference where he accuses Hillary Clinton of a series of crimes, and then exonerates her, whatever the Russians were trying to do, they couldn't have done anything worse than what James Comey did on that day. He gave a blow to the solar plexus to the Clinton campaign far beyond anything that either Donald Trump or the Russians could have done.

utterances.speaker: REINES
utterances.utterance: Joe, you can't see me nodding, but I am nodding vigorously.

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.utterance: Well, there is nothing not to nod about. The bottom line is this, while all that is going on, James Comey, John Brennan and James Clapper are trying to figure out how to subvert the candidacy of the opposing candidate. And I must say, there is absolutely irrefutable evidence now that that's exactly what they were doing. And I am perfectly happy by the way, to have a grand jury look at it and make all the decisions necessary about whether or any of that was illegal. And I'll tell you, I just think right now, watching the fight between McCabe and Comey about who lied about what during all of this tells you exactly what kind of leadership we had at the FBI and the Department of Justice in the Obama administration -- a disgraceful bunch of dirty cops.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, Philippe is not a big fan of James Comey either and I think he will admit that. He had come to "Watters' World" as are most Democrats and I always will say that Hillary would have fired Comey probably quicker than Donald J. Trump.

utterances.speaker: DIGENOVA
utterances.utterance: Why didn't Obama fire Comey after the July 5th press conference? He shouldh have been fired...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A lot of questions. REINES; You and I would be sitting here talking about obstruction of something else. I mean, the problem with 2016 is you have a lot of people...

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Listen, Philippe, we have got to run ,but the only thing Trump obstructed was Hillary getting into the White House. Up next, a judge ordered him out of his parents' home. And we are going to check with this 30-year-old, Michael Rotondo on his house hunt.

utterances.speaker: EMANUEL
utterances.utterance: Live from "America's News Headquarters," I am Mike Emanuel. Fox News obtaining a letter sent in January from President Trump's legal team to special counsel Robert Mueller arguing the President cannot be forced to testify into the investigation into Russian meddling in the 2016 election. They also argue that Mr. Trump could not have committed obstruction because he has absolute authority over all Federal investigations. A US delegation in Beijing this weekend to talk trade as fears of a global trade war escalate. US Commerce Secretary, Wilbur Ross arriving in China today in hopes of negotiating a deal that would close a large trade gap with China. The talks coming after a rocky week during which the White House moved to revive the threat of tariffs on Chinese imports and slapped Canada, Mexico and the European Union with steep metal tariffs. I am Mike Emanuel, for now, back to "Watters' World."

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Michael Rotondo is on the move. By now, you might have heard about the 30-year-old from upstate New York who last week was evicted under a court order from his parents' home after living there rent free for eight years. Rotondo spent the week packing up his things and finally moving out. He joins me now with the latest on his house hunt. All right, Mike, where are you right now?

utterances.speaker: MICHAEL ROTONDO, EVICTED FROM PARENTS' HOME
utterances.utterance: Right now I am in my cousin's sister's house.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, so you're still technically living with the family.

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: We are here because there is a nice Skype set up with the camera and microphone and it's very easy to set up very nicely.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What is the flag in the background? What flag is that?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: I don't know what this flag is. Do you know what that flag is?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: No, (inaudible).

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: This is a -- how old is he?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: He is nine.

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: This is a nine-year-old's bedroom. It's a nine-year-old's bedroom.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Got it. I want to go back a little while, because I am interested in your back story. You went to college, right?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: Briefly, yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Did you graduate from college?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: Briefly means I didn't graduate. No, I didn't graduate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So, I thought maybe you matriculated quickly because of your advanced intelligence. What was your major when you were briefly in college?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: I dropped -- I won't say that. I started with engineering and I went to business when that didn't work out.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, you dropped out of college?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Why did you drop out of college?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: My academic habits were very poor so I really couldn't just integrate into the classes very well.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, so you like engineering and you like business. When you dropped out of college, what happened next?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: I was -- I started in sales. I've held a lot of different sales jobs.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What were you selling?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: I sold vacuum cleaners. I sold dry-cleaner coupons, I sold -- I've done retail, which isn't real professional sales, but I'd done it. I had done a lot of weird things like where you kind of pitch people on the street sort of in front of businesses. I did that for a while.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Did you dress up in one of those crazy outfits that flap around in the wind? Is that what you mean?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: (Inaudible).

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, so you have had a few jobs, mostly in sales. but does that account for all eight years? You must have been unemployed for a lot of that time, right?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: No, I drove delivery, which wasn't really a sales job, but I did customer service. That was a significant -- that a year and a half, mostly it's been sales.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, were you making any money at these jobs and saving it or were you just spending it on what?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: I really wasn't saving have much, but I spent it on things that I needed.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Like what?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: Like food and just conventional things -- entertainment, food, gasoline, things like that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What kind of entertainment?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: Sometimes housing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What kind of entertainment?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: Well, bars -- you go to a bar, that's entertainment, I would say or just leisure time. Sometimes movies, but not often.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay, were you fired from a lot of these jobs or did you quit?

utterances.speaker: ROTONDO
utterances.utterance: I am not discussing my work history at this time, I'm sorry.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Okay.
